Anonymous Sat 18 Sep 2021 00:37:33 No.41714828 Report

>>41703878
Sorry for the late response; I went to bed pretty soon after posting that last bit

>where would I start if I wanted to learn Japanese?
A bit tough to say. In regards to textbooks the Genki series by Eri Banno is pretty good (it's what I used in college) but if at all possible try to find a conversation group; whether it be at your local college campus or even through Discord/Zoom. Textbooks will only get you so far; you need to give yourself an opportunity to apply it.

>How long did you study before feeling proficient enough to start translating manga on your own?
This is also a bit nuanced. I studied Japanese for three years in high school and majored it in college, and only felt comfortable enough to throw my hat into the translation ring maybe... Two years into college, so after five years of studying? That being said, if you're serious about learning Japanese, I'd actually suggest trying to start translating *way* before I did, like try translating very simple, kindergarten-level Japanese books maybe two years into studying. It's one of the best ways I can think of to get experience reading conversational Japanese, and trying to translate it at a lower proficiency level, while initially frustrating, will give you insights into grammar structures you might initially miss in the textbook or in class.
